%N A389496 Triangle T(n,k) read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of heapable permutations of length n whose major index is k.
%C A389496 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389496 The major index of a permutation p = (p1, p2, ..., pn) is the sum of the positions i (1 <= i <= n-1) where a descent occurs, that is, where pi > pi+1. Formally: maj(p) = Sum { i : pi > pi+1 }.
%C A389496 In other words, the major index is obtained by adding all indices i for which the element pi is greater than the next element pi+1.
